Engine.enginePackage

Class Janus

  • java.lang.Object
    • Engine.enginePackage.Janus
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    LocalJanus, StorytellerRemote, SwatRemote, java.rmi.Remote

    public class Janus
extends java.lang.Object
implements StorytellerRemote, LocalJanus, SwatRemote
    This is the server implementation. It provides services for running a story, navigating the log data of it, and doing rehearsals.

    The interface of the server is defined by StorytellerRemote. All of the server methods excepting StorytellerRemote.login(int, String, String) receive a session identifier to indicate over which session the operation must be applied.

    The server creates for each session threads and buffers that are used during the session lifetime. Both buffers and thread usage is bounded to preserve the server resources. In addition to bounding resources, the server has a session timeout after which inactive sessions are logout.

    The buffers used for each session may include:

    • A very small buffer for sentences meant to be delivered to storyteller.
    • A very small buffer for sentences meant to be processed by the engine.
    • A medium sized buffer for storing surface log data generated while playing a story. This log data must be downloaded by storyteller in order to have the engine continue its execution when it is full.
    • A medium sized buffer for storing detailed log data generated while playing a story. This detailed log data is generated only for small portions of a story on user demand. When the buffer is full, no more data is produced until the client empties the buffer by downloading the data.
    • Not really a buffer, but a file on disk to save intermediate engine states. These are used for collecting detailed log data.
    • A buffer for storing Rehearsal results.
    The sentence and rehearsal buffers are maintained by Janus. The log data buffers are maintained by TreeLogger. The disk file for engine states is handled by LogDataCollector. For more information information on logging workings see com.storytron.swat.loglizard.

    The detailed log data collection is delegated to the class LogDataCollector. This class handles a thread where the engine is executed solely for the purpose of collecting detailed log data.

    The threads per session are

    • A thread for running the engine playing the story.
    • A thread for running the engine collecting log data. This thread is started only if the session is started with logging enabled (usually author sessions).
    • A thread for running rehearsals.

    The server also implements logging statistics with the Statistics class. Every certain period of time the collected statistics are sent to a database.

    When starting a story with startStory(String, String, int[], byte[], boolean), a thread is created to run the engine. When the client sends or asks data, the rmi thread attending the client waits for the engine thread to synchronize with it using one of the queues Janus.SessionData.toEngine and Janus.SessionData.toStoryteller.

    On all the major requests, a time stamp in the session is updated. The time stamp tells when a session did its last meaningful interaction. If the time stamp is too old, the server can destroy the session. A task is scheduled to run periodically to destroy sessions with old time stamps.
